<HL>
   Working in Aerospace -- A Special Report
   ---
   Labor Letter:
   A Special News Report on People
   And Their Jobs in Offices,
   Fields and Factories
   ----
   By Rick Wartzman
</HL>
<DATE>
06/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR MD GE GD LK BA NOC
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   THE AX FALLS FASTER than most expected on aerospace
workers.
   U.S.-Soviet detente and congressional budget-cutting
hasten pink slips for white-collar and hourly employees
alike. McDonnell Douglas, Lockheed, GE, General Dynamics and
some small firms disclose plans to trim rolls. The Aerospace
Industries Association tracks 16,000 job-cut notices among
its 54 members in 1990, 28% ahead of its forecast. "This may
just be the beginning," warns AIA economist David Napier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The passenger-plane business, once viewed as a cushion,
doesn't help much: Boeing isn't ramping up new programs, so
it's laying off, too, and McDonnell Douglas's commercial unit
flounders. Firms search for new niches to keep employment
stable, but changing course is tough.
   "There will always be some growth areas," such as
electronics, says Karen Berk of the job-matching Aerospace
Human Resources Network.
                                                                                                       

   HANDLING HAZARDS lessen for use of aircraft "composites."
   As plane makers add more of the light, reinforced fibers
in their designs, they alert workers on how to better ply
toxic chemicals that strengthen and coat composites.
   Worker complaints decline with increased industry concern,
better training and new cautionary signs posted in plants,
the Machinists union says. A third of the cost of Lockheed's
new Palmdale, Calif., composites center is for proper
ventilation and other health controls.
   An Occupational Safety and Health Administration crackdown
last year at Boeing and Lockheed helped spur the effort. Now,
manufacturers push suppliers of advanced composites to set
specific exposure limits. "If we don't do it, they're not
going to buy from us," says David Forest, head of BASF
Structural Materials.
                                                                                                       

   PEACETIME "CONVERSION" moves ahead at federal and state
levels.
   House members prepare wording for the defense
authorization bill on the need to help defense workers brace
for the changeover. It would list worker qualifications for
relocation and other allowances when defense cuts hit. More
controversial ideas, such as requiring weapons makers to pay
for retraining and benefits, will be saved for floor debate.
   "We want to make sure at least something gets on the
table," says Rep. Nick Mavroules (D., Mass.), a member of a
bipartisan House-Senate task force on the issue. California
mulls a worker-retraining program; in Minnesota, stung by big
layoffs by Unisys, Honeywell and other defense firms, a new
0.1% payroll tax raises worker aid. Over 40 aerospace firms
met in Dayton, Ohio, last week to share tips on switching to
non-military work.
   One big challenge, says Ohio Gov. Celeste: meeting the
civilian sector's tougher delivery standards.
                                                                                                       

   LOWER YOUR WAGE RATES, the Pentagon tells Lockheed, Boeing
and other companies. They must bring pay in line with other
firms in their areas, or the government says it will find
other sources. The Defense Contract Audit Agency contests
$222 million in "unreasonable" labor charges. Unions grouse
that contractors are exploiting the issue at the bargaining
table.
                                                                                                       

   BLACK PROGRAMS, WHITE FACES: Asians, Hispanics and blacks
make up only 16% of workers in aerospace, with its often
secret, or "black," programs, lagging behind the overall
economy, the General Accounting Office finds. General
Dynamics's space division agrees to offer employment and
$270,000 in back wages to 21 minority engineers whom the
Labor Department says were wrongly denied jobs.
                                                                                                       

   BRAIN DRAIN: Of 30 companies surveyed by the AIA,
two-thirds say they're short of scientists and engineers, and
85% expect such problems in the future. So firms do more to
support education, with 40% of corporate contributions going
for aid, such as scholarships.
                                                                                                       

   OLD AEROSPACE WORKERS don't fade away -- they go back to
work.
   More cost-conscious jet makers take back retirees, for
quick, complex assignments. "We know what they're capable
of," says Vince DeBlaze, human resources director at
McDonnell Douglas's jet-fighter factory in St. Louis, which
employs about 200 of its retirees. While fast-food firms hire
many retirees for low-skill work, "we've shown you can do it
with high-tech," says ACS Management Group Inc.
   Bob Stein, a manager at Fairchild Controls, says a former
Hughes master scheduler he hired briefly for a new program to
build environmental controls for jet-fighter components "was
able to work faster and smarter -- and then press on."
   ACS's Graybeard division, a job shop for former aerospace
technicians, has 2,300 resumes.
                                                                                                       

   THE CHECKOFF: Machinists at Lockheed's
soon-to-be-shuttered, 62-year-old factory in Burbank, Calif.,
staged a rally last weekend to keep their jobs. . . . Boeing
says that for each job created outside the U.S. by its
"foreign sourcing," 20 domestic jobs are spawned. . . .
Northrop holds job fairs to recruit workers for its B-2
Stealth bomber project, saying, "You just might wind up
making history."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900605-0102
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900605-0102.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Market Ends Higher as Financial Stocks
   Spur Big Gains; Ohio Casualty Up 2 1/2
   ----
   By Craig S. Smith
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Over-the-counter stocks surged to their
highest levels so far this year, with financial stocks
leading the advance.
   Traders say investors turned to the long-dormant financial
sector in hopes that an easing interest-rate environment will
fatten profits there.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Weak non-farm employment growth in May, evident in the
Labor Department's report on Friday, and a subsequent spike
in bond prices has encouraged hopes that interest rates will
decline from current levels.
   "If rates are coming down then the financials are
certainly going to look more attractive," says Claudia Mott,
small-stock analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities. She notes
that the stocks have performed miserably so far this year.
   Insurance stocks performed particularly well, sending the
Nasdaq Insurance Index up 7.72, or more than 1.5%, to 514.86.
As of Friday's close, the index was down about 7% for the
year.
   Mary-Alice Dennehy, OTC trader at insurance-stock
specialist Conning &amp; Co., says there may be some
follow-through in insurance stocks today.
   She notes that trading activity in St. Paul Cos., the OTC
market's largest insurance stock by market capitalization,
was strong both Friday and yesterday. The stock gained 3/4 to
59 1/2 on volume of about 594,000 shares, almost three times
its average daily volume.
   Insurance companies earn higher margins with lower
interest rates, and their bond investments surge in value
when rates come down.
   Among the OTC market's other big insurance stocks that
gained were Ohio Casualty, which rose 2 1/2 to 46 1/2, and
Safeco, which gained 1 5/8 to 39 1/4.
   The buying helped push the Nasdaq Financial Index up 6.25,
or 1.6%, to 398.65. The Nasdaq 100 Index, which includes the
OTC market's largest nonfinancial stocks, gained only about
1%.
   But the rotation into financial stocks allowed the OTC
market to extend its string of gains, with the Nasdaq
Composite Index adding 3.48, or 0.75%, to 465.61 -- its
highest level so far this year.
   The New York Stock Exchange Composite Index, meanwhile,
hit a new all-time high, breaking above the 200 level with a
1.1% gain.
   OTC advancers led decliners, 1,082 to 907. National Market
System volume moderated to 107,262,500 shares from Friday's
robust 120,669,600 shares.
   Intel led the most-active list with a 1 point gain to 48
1/2. The company moved the expiration of its 1992 warrants up
to July 25. Each warrant entitles the holder to buy 1.5
shares of Intel for $45.
   Also on the list, Oracle Systems added 5/8 to 20 1/2.
Adobe Systems, however, fell 1 1/2 to 33 1/4.
   HEI added nearly 39%, up 1 5/32 to 4 1/8.
   Columbia Hospital has agreed to buy the company for $4.50
a share.
   Timberline Software has gained 2 to 12 1/2, after surging
16.7% on Friday. The company's executives tell Dow Jones
Professional Investor Report that a newsletter may be
responsible for the sudden interest in the stock. The
newsletter estimates that Timberline will earn 45 to 50 cents
a share in 1990. Timberline's chief financial officer called
the estimates "reasonable."
   Prospect Financial lost 1 to 2, after falling 20% on
Friday. The company announced Friday that it expects to
record a charge in the fourth quarter ended in April, and may
not be in compliance with certain regulatory capital
requirements as of July 1.
   Players International surged 1 5/8 to 8. The company began
test marketing 900-number telephone games based on the hit
television syndicated game shows "Jeopardy" and "Wheel of
Fortune."
   Acclaim Entertainment slid 1 1/8 to 13 1/8. Profit-taking
has hit the stock after it surged to a 52-week high last
week. Acclaim rose to 16 last Thursday, largely on the
prospects for its video game based on the television show
"The Simpsons."
</TEXT>
