   Alaska Air's May Traffic Rose
</HL>
<DATE>
06/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   ALK
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   SEATTLE -- Alaska Airlines, a unit of Alaska Air Group
Inc., said that its May traffic rose 14% to 340.4 million
revenue passenger miles from 299 million flown a year
earlier. A revenue passenger mile is one paying passenger
flown one mile.
   The month's passenger load factor, or the percentage of
available seats occupied by fare-paying passengers, rose
slightly to 50.2% from 50.9% in May 1989.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the five months ended in May, revenue passenger miles
totaled 1.62 billion, up 18% from 1.38 billion the year
earlier. The five-month load factor was 49.4%, down slightly
from 50% the year before.
</TEXT>
