<HL>
   World Bank, Affiliate
   Approve New Loans
   To Developing Nations
</HL>
<DATE>
06/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   AFRIC MDEST FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The World Bank and its affiliate, the
International Development Association, approved $440.6
million in loans to seven developing nations.
   The largest credit, $180.4 million from the IDA, will help
finance extensive road construction in Tanzania.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Algeria will get a $99.5 million loan to help restructure
various industries, while Indonesia will receive an $86
million credit to expand natural-gas lines. Both of these
loans will be provided by the World Bank.
   Other loans, all from the IDA, included $50 million to
Guinea to support private-sector enterprises and revamp the
country's banking system; $15 million to Yemen for public
health facilities; $6 million to Kenya to restructure the
country's industrial-development bank and its industrial and
commercial development corporation; and $3.7 million to
Madagascar to support agricultural research.
   The World Bank loans will be at variable interest rates,
currently 7.75% a year. The IDA credits will be interest-free
except for administrative fees.
</TEXT>
