WSJ900605-0040
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900605-0040.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Bush May Delay Drilling
   Off Florida and California
</HL>
<DATE>
06/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A26
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- President Bush is expected to delay new oil
drilling off the coasts of California and Florida so that
additional environmental studies can be done, administration
officials said.
   While cautioning that the president hadn't made a final
decision, the officials said he was likely to seek different
delays for various tracts. Some parts of Florida were likely
to be removed even from consideration for development until
early in the next century.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The long-awaited announcement, which is expected next
week, will try to steer a middle course between
environmentalists, who have pushed for a permanent ban, and
the oil industry, which is eager to resume drilling.
   By delaying a decision, the president could remove some of
the political heat from the issue in the fall election
campaign. The Florida congressional delegation and GOP
gubernatorial candidates Sen. Pete Wilson in California and
Gov. Bob Martinez in Florida all oppose new drilling.
   In his public comments, the president has hinted that he
won't allow drilling in the foreseeable future off Florida
but has left California's fate more murky.
   Lisa Speer, an attorney with the Natural Resources Defense
Council in New York, said, "A delay would have been a bold
stroke before the Exxon Valdez. But people aren't going to be
satisfied with it at this point."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900605-0039
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900605-0039.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Intel Warrants Expiration
</HL>
<DATE>
06/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   INTC
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- Intel Corp. said it accelerated the
expiration of its 1992 warrants. The company said that any
warrants not exercised will expire at the close of business
on July 25.
   Under the company's warrant agreement, Intel can
accelerate the expiration whenever the stock price closes at
$42 or higher for any 20 trading days within a period of 30
trading days. Intel said it met those conditions yesterday.
Intel's stock closed at $48.50 a share, up $1, in national
over-the-counter trading yesterday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Each warrant entitles the holder to buy one and one-half
shares of Intel's common stock for $45 a warrant exercised.
The microcomputer maker currently has 3.5 million warrants
outstanding and expects to raise about $157 million.
</TEXT>
