900605-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Justices Back
   Public School
   Religious Club
   ----
   By Stephen Wermiel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Supreme Court upheld a federal law that
requires public schools to give student religious groups the
same access to scheduling and facilities that other
extracurricular activities have.
   By an 8-1 vote, the justices ruled that a 1984 federal law
requires an Omaha, Neb., high school to accommodate a
Bible-reading club that students wanted to organize.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In an opinion written by Justice Sandra O'Connor, the
court said the law treats extracurricular activities as part
of a public forum created by the school. The federal law, the
court said, means the school can't discriminate against use
of the public forum based on a club's religious, political or
philosophical views. This approach, Justice O'Connor said,
doesn't violate the First Amendment's separation of church
and state.
   The eight justices in the majority were split into three
opinions. Six of them, including Justice O'Connor, appeared
to believe that the federal law is constitutional in all
respects. Justices Anthony Kennedy and Antonin Scalia
differed on how to analyze freedom of religion issues under
the First Amendment, but not on the law's validity.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall, joined by Justice William
Brennan, agreed that the law was constitutional as applied to
the Omaha school, but they warned that school officials must
be careful to disassociate themselves from the religious
message of the club.
   Justice John Stevens dissented.
   Officials at the Omaha school refused to allow the
religious club to meet, but a federal appeals court in St.
Louis ruled that the federal law required accommodation of
the club. The high court affirmed the appeals court ruling.
(Westside Community Board of Education vs. Mergens)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900605-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900605-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Commodore Unveils
   System Linking CD,
   Computer Functions
</HL>
<DATE>
06/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CBU
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   WEST CHESTER, Pa. -- Commodore International Ltd.
introduced a system that combines the capabilities of a
personal computer and compact disk player.
   The Commodore system, called the CDTV player, consists of
an Amiga personal computer -- without keyboard or monitor --
and a CD player. The system is hooked up to a television to
display video and text.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The CDTV Player makes the personal computer maker an early
entrant into a market that many computer companies consider
to be vast. The companies think that the home market for
computers is finally about to pick up with the introduction
of multimedia machines. For instance, they expect people to
buy encyclopedias on computer disks with video and audio
capabilities, or instructional videos that they can interact
with through the computer.
   Commodore has also broken through a price barrier. Its
CDTV Player, whose shipment date wasn't specified, will cost
less than $1,000. Application disks will cost just $25 to
$60.
   Still, the market for such systems is very young and will
take time to develop. The various companies involved haven't
agreed on what technological standards they will follow, and
it usually takes the market quite some time to sort out those
issues. It's also not clear how people will use these
systems, and whether they will want reference books or just
more games. In any case, it may take a couple of years for
companies to produce enough application disks to make these
systems attractive.
   "Commodore has a history of producing great hardware, but
they don't have enough software available," said Greg
Drahuschak, a securities analyst at Wheat First/Butcher &amp;
Singer. "That is where Commodore has always fallen short."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900605-0029
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
